BASIC CLEANUP

# Columns with 100% NA values
na_columns <- sapply(t20, function(x) mean(is.na(x))) == 1
names(na_columns[na_columns == TRUE])
## [1] "bl"            "pr_bowling"    "pr_allrounder"
cols_with_all_NA <- sapply(t20, function(x) all(is.na(x)))
t20_cleaned <- t20[, !cols_with_all_NA]


t20_cleaned$high_score_numeric <- as.numeric(gsub("[^0-9]", "", t20_cleaned$high_score))



#specific category:
t20_cleaned <- t20_cleaned %>%
  mutate(consolidated_role = case_when(
    grepl("wicketkeeper", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "WicketKeeper Batter",
    grepl("batting allrounder", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Batting Allrounder",
    grepl("bowling allrounder", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Bowling Allrounder",
    grepl("allrounder", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Allrounder",  
    grepl("batter", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Batter",
    grepl("bowler", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Bowler",
    TRUE ~ "Other" 
  ))

t20 <- t20_cleaned


# Summarize missing values by column
colSums(is.na(t20))

WicketKeepers:

wk_batters_only <- t20[t20$consolidated_role == "WicketKeeper Batter", ]

# add variables 
wk_batters_only$boundary_rate <- with(wk_batters_only, ifelse(ball_faced > 0, (`4s` + `6s`) / ball_faced, 0))
wk_batters_only$century_rate <- with(wk_batters_only, ifelse(innings > 0, `100s` / innings, 0))
wk_batters_only$not_out_rate <- with(wk_batters_only, ifelse(innings > 0, not_out / innings, 0))

wk_batting_data  <- wk_batters_only[, c("boundary_rate", "century_rate", "not_out_rate", 
                                 "average_score", "strike_rate", "high_score_numeric", "st")]



wk_batting_data$high_score_numeric <- as.numeric(gsub("[^0-9.]", "", wk_batting_data$high_score_numeric))


normalized_wk_data <- scale(wk_batting_data)
library(cluster)

silhouette_widths <- numeric(10)

for (k in 2:10) {
  set.seed(123)
  kmeans_result <- kmeans(normalized_wk_data, centers=k)
  silhouette_analysis <- silhouette(kmeans_result$cluster, dist(normalized_wk_data))
  silhouette_widths[k] <- mean(silhouette_analysis[, "sil_width"])
}

k <- which.max(silhouette_widths)
plot(2:10, silhouette_widths[-1], type='b', main="Silhouette Method for Determining k", xlab="Number of Clusters", ylab="Average Silhouette Width")

set.seed(123) 
k <- 2
final_kmeans <- kmeans(normalized_wk_data, centers=k)

# Assign cluster labels based on the silhouette method
wk_batting_data$cluster <- as.factor(final_kmeans$cluster)



library(pheatmap)
## Warning: package 'pheatmap' was built under R version 4.3.3
cluster_centers_df <- t(as.data.frame(final_kmeans$centers))

#heatmap 
pheatmap(cluster_centers_df, 
         display_numbers = TRUE, 
         scale = "row", 
         cluster_rows = FALSE)

cluster_summary<- wk_batting_data %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  summarise_all(mean, na.rm = TRUE)

print(cluster_summary)

wc_results <-  read_csv("T20WorldCupsResults.csv")

## chr (8): Team 1, Team 2, Winner, WC winner, Venue, Date, Match Type, Host Na...

##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
head(wc_results)
library(tidyr)
player_clusters_by_team <- wk_batters_only %>%
  group_by(country, cluster) %>%
  summarise(number_of_players = n(), .groups = 'drop')%>%
  spread(cluster, number_of_players, fill = 0)%>%
    mutate(country_abbreviation = case_when(
    country == "Afghanistan" ~ "AFG",
    country == "Australia" ~ "AUS",
    country == "Bangladesh" ~ "BAN",
    country == "England" ~ "ENG",
    country == "India" ~ "IND",
    country == "Ireland" ~ "IRE",
    country == "Newziland" ~ "NZ", 
    country == "Pakistan" ~ "PAK",
    country == "South Africa" ~ "SA",
    country == "Sri Lanka" ~ "SL",
    country == "West Indies" ~ "WI",
    country == "Zimbabwe" ~ "ZIM",
    TRUE ~ country 
  ))

player_clusters_by_team
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyr)

# Reshape the data to long format
player_clusters_long <- player_clusters_by_team %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(`1`, `2`), names_to = "cluster", values_to = "number_of_players") %>%
  mutate(cluster = recode(cluster, `1` = "Cluster 1", `2` = "Cluster 2")) # rename clusters

# Now plot using the reshaped data
ggplot(player_clusters_long, aes(x = country_abbreviation, y = number_of_players, fill = cluster)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge", alpha = 0.6) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Cluster 1" = "blue", "Cluster 2" = "red"),
                    name = "Cluster") +
  labs(title = "Player Clusters by Country",
       x = "Country",
       y = "Number of Players") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

# Join the player_clusters_by_team with the World Cup results data for Team 1
wc_results <- wc_results %>%
  left_join(player_clusters_by_team, by = c("Team 1" = "country_abbreviation"))

wc_results <- wc_results %>%
  left_join(player_clusters_by_team, by = c("Team 2" = "country_abbreviation"), suffix = c("_Team1", "_Team2"))

head(wc_results)
wc_results <- wc_results %>%
  drop_na()

Modelling

# Load required libraries
library(caret)
library(dplyr)

set.seed(123)

wc_results$Team1 <- as.character(wc_results$`Team 1`)
wc_results$Team2 <- as.character(wc_results$`Team 2`)

# binary target variable indicating whether the team of interest won
wc_results$winner_binary <- ifelse(wc_results$Winner == wc_results$`Team 1`, 1, 0)

# Convert Team1 and Team2 to factors if they are categorical
wc_results$Team1 <- as.factor(wc_results$Team1)
wc_results$Team2 <- as.factor(wc_results$Team2)

# Step 2: Split the data into training and testing sets
set.seed(123) # for reproducibility
training_indices <- sample(1:nrow(wc_results), size = 0.7 * nrow(wc_results))
train_data <- wc_results[training_indices, ]
test_data <- wc_results[-training_indices, ]

library(splitstackshape)
## Warning: package 'splitstackshape' was built under R version 4.3.1
dat <- stratified(wc_results, group = c("1_Team1", "2_Team1", "1_Team2", "2_Team2"), size = 0.2, bothSets = TRUE)

train_data <- dat[[2]]
test_data <- dat[[1]]

# logistic regression model
model <- glm(winner_binary ~ `1_Team1` + `2_Team1` + `1_Team2` + `2_Team2`, data = train_data, family = "binomial")

# Predict on test data
predictions <- predict(model, newdata = test_data, type = "response")
predicted_classes <- ifelse(predictions > 0.7, 1, 0)

# Convert predictions
test_data$winner_binary <- factor(test_data$winner_binary, levels = c(0, 1))
predicted_classes <- factor(predicted_classes, levels = c(0, 1))

lg_conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(data = predicted_classes, reference = test_data$winner_binary)
lg_conf_df <- as.data.frame.matrix(lg_conf_matrix$table)

shap graph & xgboost

wc_results

##xgboot

library(xgboost)
set.seed(123)
wc_results$winner_binary <- ifelse(wc_results$Winner == wc_results$`Team 1`, 1, 0)


numeric_predictors <- wc_results[, c("1_Team1", "2_Team1", "1_Team2", "2_Team2")]

set.seed(123)  
training_indices <- sample(1:nrow(wc_results), size = 0.7 * nrow(wc_results))
train_data <- numeric_predictors[training_indices, ]
test_data <- numeric_predictors[-training_indices, ]

train_labels <- wc_results$winner_binary[training_indices]
test_labels <- wc_results$winner_binary[-training_indices]

# Create DMatrix objects for XGBoost
dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(train_data), label = train_labels)
dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(test_data), label = test_labels)


params <- list(
  booster = "gbtree",
  objective = "binary:logistic",
  eta = 0.3,
  max_depth = 6,
  subsample = 0.8,
  colsample_bytree = 0.8
)

# Train model
xgb_model <- xgb.train(params = params, data = dtrain, nrounds = 100)

#Make predictions
predictions <- predict(xgb_model, dtest)
predicted_classes <- ifelse(predictions > 0.7, 1, 0)

#Convert predictions to factors for the confusion matrix calculation
predicted_classes <- factor(predicted_classes, levels = c(0, 1))
test_labels <- factor(test_labels, levels = c(0, 1))


xg_conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(predicted_classes, test_labels)
print(xg_conf_matrix)

Tuning

# DMatrix objects
dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(train_data), label = train_labels)
dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(test_data), label = test_labels)

# Define the parameter grid
params_grid <- expand.grid(
  max_depth = c(3, 5, 7, 9),
  min_child_weight = c(1, 3, 5, 7),
  gamma = c(0, 0.1, 0.2),
  subsample = c(0.6, 0.8, 1),
  colsample_bytree = c(0.6, 0.8, 1),
  eta = c(0.01, 0.1, 0.3),
  list = FALSE  
)


tuning_results <- list()

# Loop combination of parameters
for (i in seq_len(nrow(params_grid))) {
  param_list <- as.list(params_grid[i, ])

 
  param_list$max_depth <- as.integer(param_list$max_depth)
  param_list$min_child_weight <- as.integer(param_list$min_child_weight)
  param_list$gamma <- as.numeric(param_list$gamma)
  param_list$subsample <- as.numeric(param_list$subsample)
  param_list$colsample_bytree <- as.numeric(param_list$colsample_bytree)
  param_list$eta <- as.numeric(param_list$eta)
  
  # cross-validation
  cv_model <- xgb.cv(
    params = param_list,
    data = dtrain,
    nrounds = 100,
    nfold = 5,
    showsd = TRUE,
    stratified = TRUE,
    print_every_n = 10,
    early_stopping_rounds = 10,
    maximize = FALSE,
    metrics = "error"
  )
  
  
  best_iteration <- cv_model$best_iteration
  best_score <- min(cv_model$evaluation_log$test_error_mean)
  
  tuning_results[[i]] <- list(
    params = param_list,
    best_iteration = best_iteration,
    best_score = best_score
  )
}

#  best performing parameters
scores <- sapply(tuning_results, function(x) x$best_score)
best_params <- tuning_results[[which.min(scores)]]$params
#  best parameters
best_params <- list(
  max_depth = 3,
  min_child_weight = 1,
  gamma = 0.2,
  subsample = 0.6,
  colsample_bytree = 0.6,
  eta = 0.3
)


best_nrounds <- 7
final_model <- xgb.train(
  params = best_params,
  data = dtrain,
  nrounds = best_nrounds
)

# Make predictions 
final_predictions_prob <- predict(final_model, dtest)

# threshold 
final_predictions <- ifelse(final_predictions_prob > 0.7, 1, 0)

# predictions to factors for the confusion matrix calculation
predicted_classes <- factor(final_predictions, levels = c(0, 1))
actual_classes <- factor(test_labels, levels = c(0, 1)) # Ensure test_labels is the actual labels from the test set

# onfusion matrix using the 
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(predicted_classes, actual_classes)
print(conf_matrix)

# Get feature importance
importance <- xgb.importance(feature_names = colnames(conf_matrix), model = xgb_model)
xgb.plot.importance(importance)

source("a_insights_shap_functions.r")
library(shapper)
## Warning: package 'shapper' was built under R version 4.3.3
m_dat <- as.matrix(train_data)
shap_result <- shap.score.rank(xgb_model = xgb_model, 
                X_train = m_dat,
                shap_approx = FALSE)  
## Loading required package: data.table
## Warning: package 'data.table' was built under R version 4.3.1
## 
## Attaching package: 'data.table'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     transpose
## The following objects are masked from 'package:lubridate':
## 
##     hour, isoweek, mday, minute, month, quarter, second, wday, week,
##     yday, year
## The following objects are masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     between, first, last
## make SHAP score by decreasing order
shap_long <- shap.prep(shap = shap_result,
                       X_train = m_dat, 
                       top_n = 4) 
## Loading required package: ggforce
## Warning: package 'ggforce' was built under R version 4.3.1
plot.shap.summary(data_long = shap_long)
